session_history.content: educate yourself on the table ddls in database fitness_db in regard to business context and referential integrity

The fitness_db database contains five tables – Products, SaleDetails, ServiceTickets, Sales, and Customers – with defined relationships enforcing referential integrity through foreign keys.

Key Observations

  • The Customers table stores information about registered customers, including their contact details and registration date.
  • The Products table contains details about the fitness products offered, such as name, type, brand, price and stock quantity.
  • The Sales table records sales transactions, linking them to customers and potentially a salesperson, with details about the total amount and date.
  • The SaleDetails table breaks down individual sales into line items, associating each sale with specific products and quantities.
  • The ServiceTickets table tracks service requests related to products, connecting them to customers and potentially logging issue descriptions and resolution dates.
  • Referential integrity is enforced through foreign keys: SaleDetails references Sales and Products; ServiceTickets references Customers and Products; and Sales references Customers.

     NO BEFORE JOURNAL,
     NO AFTER JOURNAL,
     CHECKSUM = DEFAULT,

     (
      ProductID INTEGER NOT NULL,
      ProductName VARCHAR(100) CHARACTER SET LATIN NOT CASESPECIFIC NOT NULL,
      ProductType VARCHAR(50) CHARACTER SET LATIN NOT CASESPECIFIC,
      Brand VARCHAR(50) CHARACTER SET LATIN NOT CASESPECIFIC,
      Price DECIMAL(10,2) NOT NULL,
      StockQuantity INTEGER)
UNIQUE PRIMARY INDEX ( ProductID );
SQL DDL: fitness_db.SaleDetails 
CREATE MULTISET TABLE fitness_db.SaleDetails ,FALLBACK ,
     NO BEFORE JOURNAL,
     NO AFTER JOURNAL,
     CHECKSUM = DEFAULT,
     DEFAULT MERGEBLOCKRATIO,
     MAP = TD_MAP1
     (
      SaleDetailID INTEGER NOT NULL,
      SaleID INTEGER NOT NULL,
      ProductID INTEGER NOT NULL,
      Quantity INTEGER NOT NULL,
      UnitPrice DECIMAL(10,2) NOT NULL, 
FOREIGN KEY ( SaleID ) REFERENCES fitness_db.Sales ( SaleID ),
FOREIGN KEY ( ProductID ) REFERENCES fitness_db.Products ( ProductID ))
UNIQUE PRIMARY INDEX ( SaleDetailID );

FOREIGN KEY ( CustomerID ) REFERENCES fitness_db.Customers ( CustomerID ),
